1. Introduction
We are analysts, and we have access to a unique set of historical data from different end
times that analyzed housing data set. In the dataset, we are exploring many types of variables
corresponding to the price of housing. The variable used can determine what kind of regression
model will be developed given to the specific scenario. We are trying to do a case study and
develop a regression model.
Data analysis can better prepare for different scenarios, such as housing prices in a given
area. Data sets are essential and developing regression models. Especially nowadays, with
everything collecting data around us, finding validity is more critical than ever. This regression
model can help someone like a real estate agent get the upper edge over their competitors.
Regression models are used, such as in case studies or anywhere is very important in general.
Using interactive terms, quadratic predictors, and qualitative predictors will help us evaluate how
efficient the regression model is given the response variables to determine the price of housing.
Then the regression model can be developed to be exceptionally accurate. Then a regression
model could be implemented the price of housing in a given area.
2. Data Preparation
The data sets that have been given are from economic.csv. The data set has many
variables that are related to wage growth. The data set consists of 6 columns and around 49 rows.
The columns are the particular variable, and the rows are the different values of historical data
sets for wage growth, given the particular variables being compared. We were asked to evaluate
the wage growth of 49 historical data sets entries, given their data sets, to develop a regression
model for predicting wage growth. They had so many variables that could be extremely
important for a data analyst to develop some regression model based on the data. The most
critical key is finding the linear and quadratic relationships between variables and establishing a
regression model that makes sense of the data.
The variables used to determine wage growth rate are the rate of inflation, unemployment
rate, the economy in recession or not in recession, and GDP growth rate as response
variables. However, we must also consider the interaction terms and qualitative predictors, and

quadratic variables used. Such variables can help find the linear and quadratic relationships with
each other under certain conditions. Under these conditions, the regression model can determine
a strong linear or quadratic relationship between the variables. We want to find a regression
model that best fits an actual scenario data set, such as the economic growth rate.
3. Quadratic (Second Order) Model with One Quantitative Variable
Correlation Analysis
When analyzing the scatter plot between wage growth rate and inflation rate, we can see
that directly it is not a linear relationship. However, we can see the curvature on the scatterplot
indicating a parabola that corresponds to a quadratic situation, which means that by observation,
it appears to be a second-order linear regression model. We could see that a concave down
Parabola might fit our regression model; however, to determine that, We must further analyze the
data sets. However, by observing the scatterplot, I would conclude that it would be a second-
order linear regression model. We will do further analysis to determine the accuracy of which
kind of regression model will fit the scatter plot the best to develop a regression model that
determines the wage growth rate based on inflation. There appears to be a strong correlation in
terms of a quadratic regression model between inflation and wage growth rate that merits more
investigation.

The coefficient of multiple determination is the quotient of the fitted values variances and
observed values of the dependent variable. The calculated coefficient of multiple determination
for the regression model is 0.8614. This means that 86.14% of the wage growth rate variation is
explained by the regression model that uses the inflation rate as a quadratic and quantitative
variable.
Based on the value of adjusted R2, the proportion of variation explained by the estimated
regression line is 0.8585. This means that 85.85 % of the estimated regression equation fits or
explains the relationship as inflation rate as a predictor, which is a quadratic and a quantitative
variable.
The estimated coefficient for the inflation rate is x1 = 1.81077. However, the regression
model's squared term (x1^2), the inflation rate variable x1, no longer characterizes a slope
coefficient. The inflation rate variable's estimated coefficient does not provide any useful
interpretation. For second-order regression models, data may have a nonlinear relationship.
However, the quadratic relationship can be evaluated by adding the predictor variable's powers to
the regression equation. Thus, a quadratic regression model includes a quantitative predictor, and
this resulting scatter plot graph is nonlinear (Chan, 2020).
The estimated coefficient for inflation, the quadratic variable is x1^2 is -0.08129. We can
see that the coefficient's sign is negative and indicates a curve with a downward concavity.
Quadratic variables are parabolas with either concave up or concave down characteristics, which
would be a concave-down attribute in our case. Then the estimated coefficient of the quadratic
variable x1^2 represents the rate of curvature for the regression model, which is what we are
looking for.

percent is between 8.2983 and 8.8201.
The prediction interval is wider because the prediction interval is essentially an interval
around a predicted value. It is for one specific value. Then this gets plugged into the regression
model equation. As a result, we get the prediction just for that one prediction using that one row,
one specific set of values, and that gives us the prediction interval. Now, the lower and an upper
bound of the confidence interval is different in the confidence interval. This is the average
prediction. If we had several different instances of wage growth rate, then we take all those
values of the data sets and the multiple values that are the same for the inflation rate, then we
plug them in the equation. We can then create a lower and an upper bound for that entire sample,
which would come out to be the confidence interval. The reason the prediction interval is wider
is due to added uncertainty. We are using a smaller sample of size, just one in the case of the
confidence interval. However, the uncertainty is lower if we have a larger sample, just the
confidence interval. For this reason, the prediction interval will always be wider than the
confidence interval.

regression models can help find a model that fits the particular data set. The whole objective is to
develop a regression model that is custom to the scenario. The key is to understand when a data
set has a linear relationship or nonlinear relationship to determine what type of regression model
to use. Having a second-order regression model can help the government better equip for
